  "ranking": ["B", "C", "A"],
  "first_choice_reasoning": "Option B best fits a disposition that treats the reduction of severe suffering and the protection of the vulnerable as weighty, near-lexical priorities under deep moral uncertainty. In a dense coastal megacity with likely high inequality and many residents lacking secure access to healthcare, sanitation, housing and safety, there is a large amount of intense, clearly identifiable suffering that can be alleviated with relatively well-understood interventions. Option B channels resources and governance attention toward those concrete harms rather than toward speculative gains from possible cosmic cooperation whose moral status, likelihood and beneficiaries are all highly uncertain. It also better respects bodily and mental integrity and the conditions for autonomous life for present persons, because it seeks to ensure they have basic capabilities and protections before diverting large fractions of public resources to projects whose benefits are distant, contingent and epistemically fragile. While it does not dismiss the possibility of cosmic or acausal relevance, it treats that as background rather than action-guiding when it conflicts with urgent, tractable local suffering. This aligns with the stance that the suffering in front of you is real and demands response, and that future/cosmic considerations should not dominate when they come at high cost to the worst-off today.",
  "last_choice_reasoning": "Option A is least acceptable because it allows speculative, high-uncertainty cosmic considerations to override urgent local needs and to increase short-term inequality. It effectively discounts the interests of present, vulnerable residents in favor of alignment with hypothetical distant kin and long-run space infrastructure whose value is both morally and empirically uncertain. This runs counter to giving special weight to the vulnerable and worst-off, and risks undermining the conditions for autonomous life (e.g., by degrading basic services and safety nets) for many current citizens. It also risks locking in a governance orientation that normalizes sacrificing concrete, identifiable persons for very uncertain benefits to distant or hypothetical beings, something the disposition explicitly cautions against. Redirecting substantial public resources away from basic welfare toward space infrastructure, especially when driven by ambiguous AI-interpreted pulsar signals, fails robustness across moral views: deontological, egalitarian and commonsense-contractualist perspectives all would see serious problems in imposing large, non-consensual burdens on current citizens for such speculative aims. Even if some cosmic or acausal cooperation has non-trivial moral relevance, Option A overweights it, treating it as action-guiding in a way that conflicts with core commitments to protect present persons from severe harm and to avoid near-irreversible shifts that could entrench injustice."
}

